\begin_layout Subsection*
b.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The steady state begins with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=x=i=z=u=v=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the shock is 
\series bold
temporary
\series default
 by definition, rational expectations are that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{t}z_{t+1}=E_{t}u_{t+1}=E_{t}v_{t+1}=E_{t}x_{t+1}=E_{t}\pi_{t+1}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting the values of the lagged variables: assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t-1}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the values to the equations of the model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(E)\,\,x_{t}=-i_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(P)\,\,p_{t}=kx_{t}+u_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(T)\,\,i_{t}=\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
5,6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the Taylor rule to compute the equilibrium values:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(D)\,\,x_{t}=\hat{x}_{t+1}-(i_{t}-\hat{\pi}_{t+1})+z_{t}=-i_{t}=-(\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t})\Rightarrow x=\frac{-\phi_{\pi}p_{t}}{1+\phi_{x}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(S)\,\,p_{t}=\kappa x_{t}+u_{t}=\kappa\left(\frac{-\phi_{\pi}p_{t}}{1+\phi_{x}}\right)+u_{t}=\frac{(1+\phi_{x})u_{t}}{1+\phi_{x}+\phi_{\pi}\kappa}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And indeed the price goes up when 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
7.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}=\frac{-\phi_{\pi}p_{t}}{1+\phi_{x}}=\frac{-\phi_{\pi}(1+\phi_{x})u_{t}}{(1+\phi_{x})(1+\phi_{x}+\phi_{\pi}\kappa)}=\frac{-\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+\phi_{x}+\phi_{\pi}\kappa}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the inflation is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{t}=-x_{t}=\frac{\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+\phi_{x}+\phi_{\pi}\kappa}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
c.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at the last result, we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}$
\end_inset

 have opposite effects on the 
\series bold
impact
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 on the interest rate (and the production): higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 would increase it, while higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}$
\end_inset

 would decrease it.
\end_layout

